
              <h2>Scales</h2>

              <p><strong>Scales</strong> are used to <em>normalise values of projects</em>; few people can tell if a value of 2.3 violations per thousands of lines of code is high, fair or low. In order to help people understand and better grasp the meaning and consequences of the values, a 5-level scale has been setup. These pages give more information on the selection of thresholds for all metrics, sorted according to their origin (repository).</p>
              
              
              <ul class="list-group">

                <li class="list-group-item">
                <h4>Grimoire metrics</h4>
                <p><a href="http://metricsgrimoire.github.io/">Grimoire</a> is an open-source toolset produced by <a href="http://www.bitergia.com">Bitergia</a> that obtains data from various software repositories: source code management, issue tracking systems, communication in mailing lists, etc. Data is stored in a SQL database and can easily be retrieved to present <a href="http://dashboard.eclipse.org">awesome statistics</a> on the development process. There is a dedicated dashboard for Eclipse at <a href="http://dashboard.eclipse.org">dashboard.eclipse.org</a> that already analyses thousands of projects.</p>
                <a href="scales_grimoire.html" class="btn btn-default"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right" aria-hidden="true"></span> Get more details about Grimoire scales</a></li>
                
                <li class="list-group-item">
                <h4>Marketplace metrics</h4>
                <p>The <a href="http://marketplace.eclipse.org/">Eclipse marketplace</a> lists the products and companies that make the Eclipse ecosystem. Users can also directly install plugins from the marketplace into their own IDE by a single drag'n'drop.</p>
                <a href="scales_marketplace.html" class="btn btn-default"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right" aria-hidden="true"></span> Get more details about Marketplace scales</a></li>

                <li class="list-group-item">
                <h4>PMI metrics</h4>
                <p>The <a href="https://wiki.eclipse.org/Project_Management_Infrastructure">Project Management Infrastructure</a> (or PMI) is an Eclipse project which goal is to maintain a <a href="http://projects.eclipse.org/">repository of meta-information for all projects</a>. We use it to retrieve planning management information, and amount of information available for the SCM and ITS repositories.</p>
                <a href="scales_pmi.html" class="btn btn-default"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right" aria-hidden="true"></span> Get more details about PMI scales</a></li>

                <li class="list-group-item">
                <h4>Rule-checking metrics</h4>
                <p>We use open-source software like <a href="http://pmd.sf.net/">PMD</a> and <a href="http://findbugs.sf.net">FindBugs</a> to analyse coding practices. <a href="rules.html">Each rule</a> is tagged with one or more quality attribute it impacts, and a severity.</p>
                <a href="scales_rulechecking.html" class="btn btn-default"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right" aria-hidden="true"></span> Get more details about Rule-Checking scales</a></li>
                
                <li class="list-group-item">
                <h4>SonarQube metrics</h4>
                <p><a href="http://www.sonarqube.org">SonarQube</a> provides source code metrics for projects. There is a <a href="https://dev.eclipse.org/sonar/">dedicated instance</a> of SonarQube within the Eclipse foundation, and <a href="https://wiki.eclipse.org/Sonar">projects are welcome to use it</a>.</p>
                <a href="scales_sonarqube.html" class="btn btn-default"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-chevron-right" aria-hidden="true"></span> Get more details about SonarQube scales</a></li>
                
              </ul>
